## Decisions Made
- Layer destructive checks ahead of broad SAFE matchers: rather than narrowing `^\s*curl\s/` and `^\s*find\b`, add precise destructive entries so `isSafeCommand` rejects them via the existing `!DESTRUCTIVE_PATTERNS.some(...)` guard. Keeps the diff localized and preserves benign `curl`/`find` usage.
- Cover `wget -O <file>` explicitly while keeping `wget -O -` (stdout) safe, matching CodeRabbit's intent without breaking the existing SAFE pattern at line 84.
- Block all common shell pipelines (`| bash|sh|zsh|fish`), not just `| sh`, to avoid trivial alias bypasses.

## Problems Encountered
- CodeRabbit's suggested patch tightened `SAFE_PATTERNS` for `curl`, but doing so risked false positives on benign `curl -s ...` flows used by Knowledge Distillery scripts. Resolved by hardening `DESTRUCTIVE_PATTERNS` instead — same effect, smaller blast radius.

## Constraints Identified
- `isSafeCommand` evaluates DESTRUCTIVE_PATTERNS first, so adding entries there is sufficient and does not require touching SAFE_PATTERNS.
- The companion `src/lib/destructiveCommands.ts` is a separate, more authoritative blocklist with its own test suite; this file is a lighter read-only policy and shares no patterns with it.

